SIMPLE: fungibles
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fungibles
<hw>Fun"gi*bles</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[LL.
(<ets>res</ets>) <ets>fungibiles</ets>, probably fr. L. <ets>fungi</ets>
to discharge. ⟦ldquo⟧A barbarous term, supposed to have originated in
the use of the words <ets>functionem recipere</ets> in the
Digeste.⟦rdquo⟧ <ets>Bouvier</ets>. ⟦ldquo⟧Called <ets>fungibiles</ets>,
<ets>quia una alterius</ets> vice fungitur.⟦rdquo⟧ <ets>John
Taylor</ets> (1755). Cf. <er>Function</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Civ. Law)</fld> <def>Things which may be furnished or restored in
kind, as distinguished from specific things; -- called also
<altname>fungible things</altname>.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld> <def>Movable goods which may be
valued by weight or measure, in contradistinction from those which must
be judged of individually.</def> <rj><au>Jamieson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fungic</ent>⟦br⟧
